==> INSERT is a DML operation, JPQL does not support INSERT statements.
==> In JPA, insert operations are handled through the entity lifecycle using save() or persist().
==> If INSERT is required, we must use a native SQL query.

Question =====>>>>>  Why does Spring Data JPA allow UPDATE and DELETE in JPQL but not INSERT?

Spring Data JPA allows UPDATE and DELETE in JPQL because they operate on existing managed entities.
INSERT is not allowed because creating new entities must go through the JPA entity lifecycle using 
persist() or save() to maintain cache consistency, dirty checking, and database portability.


